    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>When to Use a Detailed Invoice</h2>
      <p>
        A detailed invoice is the right choice when your line items have different tax rates, need individual item codes for inventory tracking, or require per-item discounts. This is common in retail, wholesale, manufacturing, and any business that sells products across multiple tax categories. Unlike a simple invoice that applies a single tax rate to everything, a detailed invoice calculates tax, price with tax, and discounts on each line item separately, giving both you and your client a precise breakdown.
      </p>
      <p>
        For example, a restaurant supply company might sell food items taxed at a reduced VAT rate alongside kitchen equipment taxed at the standard rate. A consulting firm might bill hours at different rates for different team members. A wholesaler might offer volume discounts on some products but not others. In all these cases, per-item detail ensures accuracy and compliance.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Per-Item Tax Rates</h2>
      <p>
        Many jurisdictions apply different tax rates to different categories of goods and services. In the European Union, for instance, member states typically have a standard VAT rate (often 19-25%) and one or more reduced rates (often 5-10%) for essentials like food, books, or medical supplies. Some items may be zero-rated or exempt entirely. A detailed invoice that tracks tax per line item ensures you collect and report the correct amount for each category, which is essential for VAT returns and tax audits.
      </p>

      <h3>Item Codes and Units of Measurement</h3>
      <p>
        Including item codes (SKUs, part numbers, or service codes) on your invoices creates a clear link between the invoice and your product catalog or time-tracking system. When a client questions a charge or needs to process a return, the item code eliminates ambiguity. Units of measurement (pieces, hours, kilograms, meters, liters) clarify exactly what the quantity represents, preventing disputes about what was delivered versus what was invoiced.
      </p>

      <h3>Per-Item Discounts</h3>
      <p>
        Offering discounts on individual items rather than the entire invoice gives you more control over pricing. You can run promotions on specific products while keeping others at full price. You can honor negotiated rates for particular services without discounting your entire fee schedule. The detailed invoice shows the client exactly which items were discounted and by how much, creating transparency and reducing billing disputes.
      </p>

      <h3>Calculating Price with Tax</h3>
      <p>
        The "price with tax" column shows the total for each line item after tax has been applied but before any discount. This is useful for clients who need to see the tax-inclusive price for each item, which is a common requirement in business-to-consumer transactions in many countries. The discount is then applied to the tax-inclusive amount, giving you the final line total. This calculation order (subtotal, then tax, then discount on the taxed amount) is the most common approach, though some jurisdictions may require discount before tax.
      </p>
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is the difference between a simple and detailed invoice?</h3>
      <p>
        A simple invoice applies a single tax rate and discount to the entire invoice. A detailed invoice allows you to set individual tax rates, item codes, units of measurement, and discounts for each line item separately. This is essential for businesses that sell products with different VAT rates or offer item-specific promotions.
      </p>

      <h3>When should I use per-item tax rates instead of a single rate?</h3>
      <p>
        Use per-item tax rates when your products or services fall under different tax categories. For example, in many countries food items are taxed at a reduced rate while electronics are taxed at the standard rate. Professional services might be exempt from VAT entirely. Per-item tax rates ensure each line item is taxed correctly for accurate accounting and legal compliance.
      </p>

      <h3>What is an item code and why include it on invoices?</h3>
      <p>
        An item code (also called SKU, product code, or part number) is a unique identifier for each product or service. Including item codes on invoices helps both the seller and buyer match invoice line items to specific products in their inventory or accounting systems. It reduces errors, speeds up payment processing, and simplifies returns or disputes.
      </p>

      <h3>What units of measurement should I use on invoices?</h3>
      <p>
        Use standard abbreviations that your industry recognizes: pcs (pieces), hrs (hours), kg (kilograms), m (meters), L (liters), or units specific to your field. Be consistent across all invoices. The unit clarifies what the quantity represents and prevents misunderstandings about what was delivered and what is being charged.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I apply different discount types to different items?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes, this detailed invoice generator lets you set a percentage discount or flat amount discount on each line item individually. This is useful for volume discounts on specific products, promotional pricing on selected items, or negotiated rates for particular services while keeping other items at full price.
      </p>

